So, we have that;
- The acquisition cost by offering the $40\%$ of its stocks is $\$47,600,000$, and;

- The acquisition cost by cash is $\$51,500,000$ (given value).

First, let's recall that the **Net Present Value** $(\operatorname{NPV})$ of the merger is determined as follows,
$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{NPV}=V_{B}^{*}-\text { Cost to Firm } A \text { of the acquisition }
\end{equation}
$$

Where, 

$V_{B}^{*}$ is the Total Value of Firm $B$ to Firm $A$:
$$V_{B}^{*}=V_{B}+\Delta V$$
Where $\Delta V$ is the net incremental gain from a merger.

So, we have that;
- The Net present value of the first option is $\$6,400,000$, and;

- The Net present value of the second option is $\$2,500,000$.
